             the officer had got Smith and the buckles while we were gone to Justice Sherwood's, and we found them there when we returned.</p>
               <p>(The buckles were produced in court, and deposed to by the prosecutor.)</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17741019-9-person140">
                  William
                   Jones
               <interp inst="t17741019-9-person140" type="surname" value="Jones"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17741019-9-person140" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17741019-9-person140" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable; another constable had brought the prisoner Dakins to the watch house. I saw her there about eight in the morning; then I went to the Punch Bowl, where Smith was with other persons; I asked there who had the man's buckles? Smith directly said she had them, and she took them out of the room where the man lay, left somebody else should; and that she did not take them with an intent to steal them; then she gave me the buckles, and immediately followed me to the watch house.</p>
               <p>Smith's Defence.</p>
               <p>I took them in order to take care of them for the prosecutor.</p>
               <p>Dakins's Defence.</p>
               <p>I know nothing of it.</p>
               <p>They called no witnesses.</p>
               <p>Both <rs id="t17741019-9-verdict49" type="verdictDescription">
